{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512960","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512960"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:03:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:03:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11982"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11982","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11982"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.15,0.1,0.08,0.66]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4572"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111157"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4572","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4572"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11982"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93281"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"45"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1924"},{"type":"tags","id":"4625"},{"type":"tags","id":"9013"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6856"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6892"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8603"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10418"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14014"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15859"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45186"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111157","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111157"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with acute neurological symptoms and is diagnosed with a left intraparenchymal haemorrhage. He is admitted to hospital and managed conservatively. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears stable with vital signs within normal limits. Cranial nerve examination is normal with no dysarthria. His speech is fluent but inappropriate to the conversation context, and he demonstrates impaired comprehension. He is right-handed and an English speaker with normal hearing.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most indicative of pathology to Wernicke\u0027s area?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inability to count to 20 due to fatigue","Inability to name a pencil","Difficulty following a conversation with multiple speakers","Inability to recognise familiar faces","Difficulty in producing a sentence that makes sense"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of Wernicke\u0027s aphasia following a left hemisphere stroke. Wernicke\u0027s area, located in the posterior temporal lobe of the dominant (usually left) hemisphere, is crucial for language comprehension and the production of meaningful speech.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDifficulty in producing a sentence that makes sense \u003C/strong\u003Eis the hallmark feature of Wernicke\u0027s aphasia. These patients typically demonstrate fluent but meaningless speech (sometimes called \u0027word salad\u0027) and significantly impaired comprehension of both spoken and written language.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInability to count to 20 due to fatigue\u003C/strong\u003E suggests bulbar dysfunction or generalised weakness, which would be associated with brainstem or bilateral hemisphere pathology rather than a focal lesion in Wernicke\u0027s area.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInability to name a pencil\u003C/strong\u003E describes anomic aphasia, which typically occurs with lesions in the temporal-parietal junction or angular gyrus. While naming difficulties may occur in Wernicke\u0027s aphasia, comprehension deficits are more characteristic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDifficulty following a conversation with multiple speakers\u003C/strong\u003E could occur in various cognitive or hearing disorders and is not specifically diagnostic of Wernicke\u0027s aphasia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInability to recognise familiar faces\u003C/strong\u003E describes prosopagnosia, which occurs with lesions of the fusiform gyrus in the temporal lobe. This is anatomically and functionally distinct from Wernicke\u0027s area.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Wernicke\u0027s aphasia is characterised by fluent but meaningless speech with impaired comprehension","Difficulty understanding spoken language is the hallmark feature of Wernicke\u0027s aphasia","Left posterior temporal lobe lesions typically cause Wernicke\u0027s aphasia"],"references":["Sheppard SM, Sebastian R. Diagnosing and managing post-stroke aphasia. Expert Rev Neurother. 2021;21(2):221-234. doi:10.1080/14737175.2020.1855976","Hillis AE. Aphasia: progress in the last quarter of a century. Neurology. 2007 Jul 10;69(2):200-13. doi: 10.1212/01.wnl.0000265600.69385.6f. PMID: 17620554.","Mesulam MM. Large-scale neurocognitive networks and distributed processing for attention, language, and memory. Ann Neurol. 1990 Nov;28(5):597-613. doi: 10.1002/ana.410280502. PMID: 2260847.","Robert Teasell MD, Norhayati Hussein MBBS MRehabMed, Ricardo Viana MD, Sarah Donaldson BHSc, Mona Madady MSc. Stroke rehabilitation clinical handbook. Canadian Stroke network. Available from: http://www.ebrsr.com/sites/default/files/Chapter%201_Clinical%20Consequences_0.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93281"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11982"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRev